The indicative in the apodosis (where we might have expected the subj. sustulisset) gives liveliness to the narration, and emphasizes the certainty with which his death would have followed the fall of the tree, had not Faunus interposed. It represents a thing (M. 348, c.) as is it had already occurred, in order to show how near it was to happening. —In the last three verses there is a graceful allusion to the difference between

Mmenas and Horace in wealth. Each is to show his gratitudo to the gods by offerings proportioned to his means.
